The Q factor is generally defined as a dimensionless value that describes how strong the resonance is and the bandwidth of resonance [22]. In electric circuits, the Q factor represents how much the peak voltage increases when the system resonates at resonant frequency. From this concept, the equation of Q factor can be express as the formula below [23]:7Q=2πEnergystoredEnergydissipatedpercycleorQ=fcΔf\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
