				\begin{document}$$Q = 2\pi \frac{Energy\,stored}{Energy\,dissipated\,per\,cycle }or\;Q = \frac{{f_{c} }}{\Delta f}$$\end{document}

From the equation above, it is inferred that a high Q factor comes with a narrow resonant bandwidth, but high voltage gain is obtained at resonance. Further, this equation also indicates that the Q factor is inversely proportional to the energy dissipated per cycle. The specific Q factor for capacitor C and inductor L at frequency ω is given by8CapacitorQfactor:QC=1ωRcC=XcRc,\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
